        "monster_family": {
          "name": "Arboreal",
          "subtype": "monster_family",
          "type": "stat_block_section"
        },
        "name": "Arboreal",
        "sections": [
          {
            "name": "Felled Arboreals",
            "sources": [
              {
                "errata": {
                  "alt": "1.1",
                  "aonid": 221,
                  "game-obj": "Sources",
                  "name": "1.1",
                  "type": "link"
                },
                "link": {
                  "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                  "aonid": 221,
                  "game-obj": "Sources",
                  "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                  "type": "link"
                },
                "name": "Monster Core",
                "page": 24,
                "type": "source"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Arboreals have a great respect for dead members of their species. Their elaborate burial rituals involve laying the fallen arboreal down in a mossy bed in the center of a grove of saplings. The decomposing arboreal nourishes the saplings, ensuring the growth of a new generation of trees.",
            "type": "section"
          },
          {
            "name": "Fungus Networks",
            "sources": [
              {
                "errata": {
                  "alt": "1.1",
                  "aonid": 221,
                  "game-obj": "Sources",
                  "name": "1.1",
                  "type": "link"
                },
                "link": {
                  "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                  "aonid": 221,
                  "game-obj": "Sources",
                  "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                  "type": "link"
                },
                "name": "Monster Core",
                "page": 24,
                "type": "source"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Particularly old arboreal regents and other powerful arboreals can tap into the extensive network of fungus that connects the roots of all the trees in the forest. By doing so, the arboreal can learn of threats throughout the entire woodland, even from miles away.",
            "type": "section"
          },
          {
            "name": "Late Bloomers",
            "sources": [
              {
                "errata": {
                  "alt": "1.1",
                  "aonid": 221,
                  "game-obj": "Sources",
                  "name": "1.1",
                  "type": "link"
                },
                "link": {
                  "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                  "aonid": 221,
                  "game-obj": "Sources",
                  "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
                  "type": "link"
                },
                "name": "Monster Core",
                "page": 24,
                "type": "source"
              }
            ],
            "text": "Though they grow faster than trees, arboreals take decades to reach maturity. They spend their early years rooted in place, developing an affinity with the flora of their homeland and attuning to its rhythms while adult arboreals keep a watchful eye on their progress. After their first century, young arboreals become more mobile, often apprenticing with senior arboreals in their territory as they learn to take up the mantle of forest guardians.",
            "type": "section"
          }
        ],
        "sources": [
          {
            "errata": {
              "alt": "1.1",
              "aonid": 221,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "1.1",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "link": {
              "alt": "Monster Core pg. 24",
              "aonid": 221,
              "game-obj": "Sources",
              "name": "Monster Core pg. 24",
              "type": "link"
            },
            "name": "Monster Core",
            "page": 24,
            "type": "source"
          }
        ],
        "text": "Arboreals are guardians of the forest and representatives of the trees. As long-lived as the woods they watch over, arboreals consider themselves parents and shepherds of trees rather than their gardeners. Consequently, while arboreals tend to be slow and methodical, they are terrifyingly swift when forced to fight in defense of the woods. Though they rarely seek out the companionship of short-lived folk\u2014even elves are fugacious in the eyes of arboreals\u2014and have an inherent distrust of change, arboreals have been known to tolerate those who seek to learn from their long-winded, rambling monologues, especially if such pupils also express a desire to protect the timberlands. Against those who threaten their realm, such as loggers eager to harvest lumber or settlers aiming to establish croplands or a town, arboreals' wrath is unwavering and devastating. Perhaps ironically, arboreals are gifted at tearing down what others build\u2014a trait that serves vengeful members of their kind well.",
        "type": "monster_family"
      },
